 origin): from a Norman French personal name <i>Dreus</i> based on ancient Germanic <i>Drogo</i>, the name of one of the sons of Charlemagne (compare Gothic <i>driugan</i> ‘to serve as a soldier’). In Old French this name became <i>Dreus</i>, <i>Drues</i> (nominative) and <i>Dru</i>, <i>Driu</i>, <i>Dreu</i> (accusative) and was introduced to England by the Normans. For further information about this name, see also   Montague  .","English: from the personal name <i>Drew</i>, a pet form of   Andrew   which was confused with the same name of Old French origin (see 1 above).","Irish: when not an adoption of the English surname, a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Druaidh</b> or <b>Ó Druaidh</b> or <b>Ó Draoi</b> ‘son’ and ‘descendant of the druid’, from <i>draoi</i> ‘druid’, genitive <i>druadh</i> or <i>draoi</i>. All of these were often Anglicized as   Drury  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Drews","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Gerhard, Gunter, Hans, Heinz, Helmut, Otto, Reinhold, Bernd, Detlef, Egon, Erna.","English: variant of   Drew   with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is also found in Guernsey in the Channel Islands.","Americanized form of German, Danish, and Dutch   Drewes  ."]},{"name":"Drewer","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Droart</i>, <i>Drouart</i> (which is probably from ancient Germanic <i>Droghard</i>, with the first element as in   Drew   + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy’)."]},{"name":"Drewett","meanings":["English (Wiltshire, Berkshire, and Surrey): of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Druet</i>, a diminutive of <i>Drue</i>, <i>Dreu</i> (from ancient Germanic <i>Drogo</i>); see   Drew   1. Alternatively, the name may be from a diminutive of Old French <i>dru</i> ‘lover’; see   Drew   4."]},{"name":"Dronet","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alcee, Desire, Olympe.","French (mainly Loire-Atlantique): from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Dron</i>, derived from the ancient Germanic name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>drog</i>, presumably meaning ‘battle’ (see also   Drew  )."]},{"name":"Droz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Aida, Cruz Maria, Diego, Jose, Miguel, Milagros, Nydia, Osvaldo, Rodriguez, Vidal.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>drog</i>, presumably meaning ‘battle’ (see also   Drew  ). This surname is also found in Puerto Rico."]},{"name":"Drea","meanings":["Irish (Kilkenny): shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Draoi</b> (see   Drew  )."]},{"name":"Montague","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from either Montaigu-le-bois (Manche) or Montaigu (Manche, Aisne), named with Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ + <i>agu</i> ‘pointed’ (from Latin <i>acutus</i>). Drogo de Montagud was a companion of William the Conqueror and founder of the <b>Montagu(e)</b> family, among whom the personal name <i>Drogo</i> was revived in the 19th century. Another family of the name <b>Monatgu</b> have held the titles of Duke of Montagu, Earl of Sandwich, Earl and Duke of Manchester, Earl of Halifax, and Earl of Beaulieu, and.","Irish: adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Taidhg</b> (see   McTigue  )."]},{"name":"Drouin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Armand, Benoit, Jacques, Andre, Clermont, Emile, Gaston, Gilles, Ovide, Pierre, Serge.","French: from a pet form of the Old French personal name <i>Droue</i>, a variant of <i>Dreue</i>, which is from the ancient Germanic name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names based on the element <i>drog</i>, presumably meaning ‘battle’ (see also   Drew  ). Compare   Derouen  ,   Derouin  , and   Tron  ."]},{"name":"Drouhard","meanings":["French:","from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Droghard</i>, composed of the elements <i>drog</i> (presumably meaning ‘battle’; see also   Drew  ) and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’.","alternatively, a derivative of the ancient Germanic name <i>Drogo</i>, a short form of compound names like <i>Droghard</i> (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Drieu","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Thanh, Chau, Minh, Quang, Vinh, Cuong, Dat, Long, Dieu, Duc, Dung, Phong, Hang, Chi, Han, Ho, Hon, So, Tong, Young, Chang, Hoa Kim, Sinh, Sun Cha, Thai.","Vietnamese (<b>Triệu</b>): from the Chinese surname 趙, see   Zhao   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Zhao","meanings":["‘Surpassing’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":10,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705182,"age":41,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Drieu Drury was born in 1025, in Normandy, France as the son of Pere Dreu Druri. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1076, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1025–1076":"1025–1076","–Male":"Surnud","1047–Male":"1047–Surnud","1015–1080":"1015–1080","1080":"1080","1015":"1015","1025":"1025","1047":"1047","1035":"1035","1066":"1066","1076":"1076","from 1060 to 1080":"1060 kuni 1080","Norm